I would make this again, but would ABSOLUTELY increase the amount of ginger and crushed red pepper. I also would recommend adding bamboo shoots and water chestnuts. And leave out the corn starch... corn starch always gives this soup kind of a gelatinous quality... I think it's much better with a thin broth. Other good additions would include straw mushrooms and lemongrass.

Rating: 3
Something is missing, but you can fix that by adding 1/2 to 1 Tablespoon of lemon juice (for a more Chinese flavor) or lime juice (for a more Thai flavor). And always leave out the pasta/bean thread noodles since they distract from the flavor and make the soup too thick. To simplify this down to a 10-minute recipe with little loss of flavor, substitute 4 c. water and boullion cubes for the broth, fresh mushrooms instead of dried (there's only a slight flavor change if you use white mushrooms instead of cremini), and don't worry about saute-ing the ginger (although this lessens its impact slightly). Then just heat the water to a boil, throw everything into the pot, and let it simmer for 5 minutes before adding the vinegar/corn startch and lemon or lime juice. In a pinch, you can also substitute powdered ginger instead of fresh. I first discovered this recipe 4 years ago and have been making variations on it regularly ever since. It's well worth trying.

